data.content:
**In .NET 11, all your sync Cosmos DB calls will throw at runtime — no opt-in can save them.**

In EF Core 10, the Cosmos provider deprecated sync I/O but allowed a sync-over-async opt-in. **EF Core 11 fully removes that opt-in.** Calling `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, or `SaveChanges()` against Cosmos **always throws**.

### Fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

This is a **medium-impact** breaking change. Every caller of these repository methods will also need to be updated to `await` the results, so the async conversion will ripple up through your call chain.
